<li id="cite_note-127"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-127">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The relation of the equestrian order to the "public horse" and Roman cavalry parades and demonstrations (such as the <i><a href="Lusus_Troiae" title="Lusus Troiae">Lusus Troiae</a></i>) is complex, but those who participated in the latter seem, for instance, to have been the <i>equites</i> who were accorded the high-status (and quite limited) seating at the theatre by the <i><a href="Lex_Roscia_theatralis" title="Lex Roscia theatralis">Lex Roscia theatralis</a></i>. Senators could not possess the "public horse." See <a href="../T.P._Wiseman" title="T.P. Wiseman" class="mw-redirect">T.P. Wiseman</a>, "The Definition of <i>Eques Romanus</i>," <i>Historia</i> 19.1 (1970) 67–83, especially pp. 78–79.</span></li>
