<li id="cite_note-273"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-273">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">With the crank and connecting rod system, all elements for constructing a steam engine (invented in 1712) — <a href="Hero_of_Alexandria" title="Hero of Alexandria">Hero</a>'s <a href="Aeolipile" title="Aeolipile">aeolipile</a> (generating steam power), the <a href="Pneumatic_cylinder" title="Pneumatic cylinder">cylinder</a> and <a href="Piston" title="Piston">piston</a> (in metal force pumps), non-return <a href="Valves" title="Valves" class="mw-redirect">valves</a> (in water pumps), <a href="Gearing" title="Gearing" class="mw-redirect">gearing</a> (in water mills and clocks) — were known in Roman times.<a href="#CITEREFRittiGreweKessener2007">Ritti, Grewe &amp; Kessener 2007</a>, p.&#160;156, fn. 74</span></li>
